"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now, we've given them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00, the Exodus company was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board the vehicles."
The company dispersed, each person joining their unit, and the sergeants had them board the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren cast a glance toward one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to look around.
"Yeah, he always has," replied Cohren as the tank turret creaked open to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks were on their way," declared the commander calmly, but clearly through his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to move forward. The Kronos that Cohren was on jolted when its brakes were released and it started moving to form up. The tanks spread out in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, whose name was Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, right?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Shit, we should be able to see it from the road we're on."
"Well, I'll hold strong for the Federation," said Orson a little provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you, 18 years old, take cover as soon as they hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll find out soon," said Corhen with a laugh. Orson didn't continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are detecting thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed onto the top of the vehicle and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yeah, I see them," replied Cohren via his throat microphone.
"Enemies?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to tell," declared Cohren. He activated his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, do not fire unless you are fired upon, let's get them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures changed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, grabbed it, and then rushed back toward the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts," shouted Shaw over the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while the soldiers jumped from the vehicles to take cover behind them. An anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed behind the formation, exploding and throwing debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew climbed out and dove for cover as the ammunition caught fire.
"Iron 1-2 and &-", 25 degrees right, 275 meters. "Fire," yelled the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, throwing mud and stones into the air.
"Send in the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged from it. He barked orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed outside. Their thin metallic arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted forward. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we capture them," said Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safely with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw marched toward the individual, who was beginning to rise. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to get rid of this man?"
